msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/chebyshev.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.chebyshev.chebfit:110
msgid ""
"The solution is the coefficients of the Chebyshev series `p` that minimizes "
"the sum of the weighted squared errors"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/chebyshev.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.chebyshev.chebfit:113
msgid ""
"E = \\sum_j w_j^2 * |y_j - p(x_j)|^2,\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/chebyshev.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.chebyshev.chebfit:115
msgid ""
"where :math:`w_j` are the weights. This problem is solved by setting up as "
"the (typically) overdetermined matrix equation"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/chebyshev.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.chebyshev.chebfit:118
msgid ""
"V(x) * c = w * y,\n"
"\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/chebyshev.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.chebyshev.chebfit:120
msgid ""
"where `V` is the weighted pseudo Vandermonde matrix of `x`, `c` are the "
"coefficients to be solved for, `w` are the weights, and `y` are the observed "
"values.  This equation is then solved using the singular value decomposition "
"of `V`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/chebyshev.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.chebyshev.chebfit:125
msgid ""
"If some of the singular values of `V` are so small that they are neglected, "
"then a `~exceptions.RankWarning` will be issued. This means that the "
"coefficient values may be poorly determined. Using a lower order fit will "
"usually get rid of the warning.  The `rcond` parameter can also be set to a "
"value smaller than its default, but the resulting fit may be spurious and "
"have large contributions from roundoff error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../../../../../.conda/lib/python3.13/site-packages/numpy/polynomial/chebyshev.py:docstring
#: of numpy.polynomial.chebyshev.chebfit:132
msgid ""
"Fits using Chebyshev series are usually better conditioned than fits using "
"power series, but much can depend on the distribution of the sample points "
"and the smoothness of the data. If the quality of the fit is inadequate "
"splines may be a good alternative."
msgstr ""

